    },
    {
      "id": "h_cKYVubrxtzmBUTPK8rU",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 155.2000274658203,
      "y": 4705.100112915039,
      "width": 1096.731201171875,
      "height": 525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6O",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1372970109,
      "version": 144,
      "versionNonce": 1821402739,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782324017799,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "CHALLENGE 2  Match Temperature to Task\nDo this:\n11.        Pick three different tasks from the list below — \n              run each at the temperature you think fits best, then at the opposite extreme:\n12.          · Write a formal definition of photosynthesis\n13.          · Write a tagline for a new sneaker brand\n14.          · Give me step-by-step instructions for boiling an egg\n15.          · Write the opening line of a sci-fi novel\nWhat to notice:\n–        Factual / instructional tasks are almost always better at low temperature — \n          the answer should not vary\n–        Creative tasks benefit from higher temperature — variation is a feature, not a bug\n–        This is the core product decision every AI tool designer makes: \n          what is this for, and how creative should it be?\n",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "CHALLENGE 2  Match Temperature to Task\nDo this:\n11.        Pick three different tasks from the list below — \n              run each at the temperature you think fits best, then at the opposite extreme:\n12.          · Write a formal definition of photosynthesis\n13.          · Write a tagline for a new sneaker brand\n14.          · Give me step-by-step instructions for boiling an egg\n15.          · Write the opening line of a sci-fi novel\nWhat to notice:\n–        Factual / instructional tasks are almost always better at low temperature — \n          the answer should not vary\n–        Creative tasks benefit from higher temperature — variation is a feature, not a bug\n–        This is the core product decision every AI tool designer makes: \n          what is this for, and how creative should it be?\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "4xPA-DqV2km0SU5EEJ4B9",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 136.40000915527344,
      "y": 5367.30012512207,
      "width": 1177.3990478515625,
      "height": 525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6P",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 515300147,
      "version": 178,
      "versionNonce": 803581501,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782324017799,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "CHALLENGE 3  Token Capping\nDo this:\n16.        Set TEMPERATURE = 1.0 and MAX_TOKENS = 30 — \n              run a question that should produce a long answer\n17.        Observe where the response cuts off\n18.        Set MAX_TOKENS = 400 — run the same question\n19.        Now try to find the minimum MAX_TOKENS that still produces a complete, \n              useful answer for a short task\nWhat to notice:\n–        Token limits are a cost and UX decision — in real products, lower limits reduce API cost \n          but frustrate users with cut-off answers\n–        Notice the AI does not know it is going to be cut off — \n          it just stops mid-thought when the limit hits\n–        Finding the minimum useful token count is a real skill in production AI development\n",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "CHALLENGE 3  Token Capping\nDo this:\n16.        Set TEMPERATURE = 1.0 and MAX_TOKENS = 30 — \n              run a question that should produce a long answer\n17.        Observe where the response cuts off\n18.        Set MAX_TOKENS = 400 — run the same question\n19.        Now try to find the minimum MAX_TOKENS that still produces a complete, \n              useful answer for a short task\nWhat to notice:\n–        Token limits are a cost and UX decision — in real products, lower limits reduce API cost \n          but frustrate users with cut-off answers\n–        Notice the AI does not know it is going to be cut off — \n          it just stops mid-thought when the limit hits\n–        Finding the minimum useful token count is a real skill in production AI development\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "BBG2xxwTtPlvt0v6Ge5Ah",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 175.2000274658203,
      "y": 6245.900131225586,
      "width": 1123.639404296875,
      "height": 455,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffec99",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6Q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1131119987,
      "version": 71,
      "versionNonce": 1832984595,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1782324017799,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "CHALLENGE 4  Build the Config Decision Table\nDo this:\n20.        Open a blank text file (or your notes app)\n21.        Create a simple table with three columns: Task, Ideal Temperature, Why\n22.        Fill in five rows with tasks you would actually want an AI tool to do — be specific\n23.        Share one row with the class at the end of the session\nWhat to notice:\n–        This forces deliberate thinking rather than just experimentation\n–        The best answers will show students already thinking like product designers — \n          'what should this tool optimise for?'\n–        Teacher: collect interesting ones verbally at the end of the session and \n          reference them in the next session's hook\n",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "CHALLENGE 4  Build the Config Decision Table\nDo this:\n20.        Open a blank text file (or your notes app)\n21.        Create a simple table with three columns: Task, Ideal Temperature, Why\n22.        Fill in five rows with tasks you would actually want an AI tool to do — be specific\n23.        Share one row with the class at the end of the session\nWhat to notice:\n–        This forces deliberate thinking rather than just experimentation\n–        The best answers will show students already thinking like product designers — \n          'what should this tool optimise for?'\n–        Teacher: collect interesting ones verbally at the end of the session and \n          reference them in the next session's hook\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
